					<a href="javascript:void(null)" class="linkTextBold" onclick="openResult('/DisplayDocument?id=366275')">20 Smart Strategies</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a target="new" class="linkTextSmall" href="/1_researchanalysis/executive_programs/0902club.pdf">(PDF)</a> <!-- <a target="new" class="linkTextSmall" href="/1_researchanalysis/executive_programs/0702Club.ppt">(PPT)</a> -->
							<br>
							<!-- <span class="contentText">Executive Summary:</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a target="new" class="linkTextSmall" href="/2_events/executive_programs/premier_march2002.pdf">(PDF)</a>&nbsp;<a class="linkTextSmall" href="javascript:void(null)" onclick="openResult('/2_events/executive_programs/premier_march2002.htm')">(HTML)</a><br> -->
							<a href="javascript:void(null)" class="linkTextSmall" onclick="openBio('/AnalystBiography?authorId=13329')">Roger Woolfe</a> &nbsp;<a href="javascript:void(null)" class="linkTextSmall" onclick="openBio('/AnalystBiography?authorId=18482')">Marcus Blosch</a> &nbsp;<a href="javascript:void(null)" class="linkTextSmall" onclick="openBio('/AnalystBiography?authorId=21282')">Jeff Sampler</a>
							<br>
							<span class="contentText">Time was when strategy was relatively straightforward. You chose to differentiate your business on the basis of a parameter like cost or quality, then worked out how to get there. Not any more.  Now there are many permutations.  Strategies come in many different shapes and sizes - and fashions. 'Focus on core competencies',  'select and concentrate on a value discipline', 're-engineer your processes', and 'manage by chaos' are just some of the catch cries adopted by businesses in the 1990s in an attempt to out-strategize the competition. In today's more chastened world, other approaches are gaining attention such as 'strategy as synchronization' and 'strategy by incrementalism'. What are the distinctive characteristics of the many different approaches to strategy, what are their sources, and where do they work best?</span>
					
